omen and men are equal? And if so, what are the factors that promote equality?Theory of Women in Religions offers an economic model to shed light on the forces that have impacted the respective statuses of women and men from the earliest developmental stages of society through the present day. Catherine Wessinger integrates data and theories from anthropology, archaeology, sociology, history, gender studies, and psychology into a concise history of religions introduction to the complex relationship between gender and religion. She argues that socio-economic factors that support specific gender roles, in conjunction with religious norms and ideals, have created a gendered division of labor that both directly and indirectly reinforces gender inequality. Yet she also highlights how as the socio-economic situation is changing religion is being utilized to support the transition toward women’s equality, noting the ways in which many religious representations of gender change over time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aWomen and religion. 7aRELIGION / Sexuality & Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aDorothy Dinnerstein.  aErnestine Friedl.  aGloria Steinem.  aLGBTQ persons and religion.  aLeadership Conference of Women Religious.  aLinda E. Olds.  aMalala Yousafzai.  aMarija Gimbutas.  aNancy Chodorow.  aandrogyny.  acomplementarity.  aeconomic theory.  afemale genital cutting.  afemale genital mutilation.  afemale infanticide.  afemale self-esteem.  afeminism.  aforaging.  afully human.  agender and religion.  agender roles.  agender.  agendercide.  agoddess.  ahorticulture.  aintensive agriculture.  aintersectionality.  ainvasion theory.  amutuality.  aorigin of patriarchy.  apatriarchy.  arites of passage.  asame-sex marriage.  atransgender.  awoman shaman.  aw